  <item>
    <title>Why I Design in the Browser</title>
    <dc:creator>milo</dc:creator>
    <content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>There&rsquo;s a common belief that design happens in Figma and engineering happens in VS Code. I&rsquo;ve never worked that way.</p>

<p>When I design in the browser, I&rsquo;m making decisions with real constraints &mdash; viewport widths, font rendering, interaction latency. The result is software that feels considered, because it was considered in the medium it lives in.</p>

<h3>The handoff problem</h3>
<p>Every handoff is a lossy compression. Designers specify intent; engineers interpret it. The gap between those two things is where quality dies. By working in both mediums simultaneously, I eliminate that gap entirely.</p>

<h3>When Figma still matters</h3>
<p>I&rsquo;m not anti-Figma. It&rsquo;s excellent for exploration, stakeholder alignment, and design system documentation. But it&rsquo;s a sketch tool, not a delivery tool. The final artifact should always be code.</p>

<blockquote><p>&ldquo;The best interfaces don&rsquo;t ask to be noticed. They hold the weight of the content they carry.&rdquo;</p></blockquote>

<h3>My workflow</h3>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Sketch loosely</strong> in Figma (30 minutes, not 3 days)</li>
  <li><strong>Build a prototype</strong> in code (React + Tailwind)</li>
  <li><strong>Iterate with real data</strong> until it feels right</li>
  <li><strong>Ship</strong></li>
</ol>

<p>This approach isn&rsquo;t for every team. But for small, fast-moving teams that care about craft, it&rsquo;s the fastest path to something great.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
    <excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[Design and engineering shouldn't live in separate tools. Here's how designing in the browser produces better software, faster.]]></excerpt:encoded>
