  <!-- ── Post 2 ──────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <item>
    <title>Building Calm Software</title>
    <dc:creator>milo</dc:creator>
    <content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>Most software is loud. Notifications, modals, badges, banners &mdash; every element competing for attention. I think there&rsquo;s a better way.</p>

<p>Calm software respects the user&rsquo;s time and attention. It surfaces information when needed, stays quiet when it&rsquo;s not, and never makes you feel behind.</p>

<h3>Principles of calm design</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Progressive disclosure.</strong> Show only what&rsquo;s needed at each step.</li>
  <li><strong>Sensible defaults.</strong> The software should work well out of the box.</li>
  <li><strong>Quiet confidence.</strong> Good UI doesn&rsquo;t need to explain itself.</li>
  <li><strong>Reversible actions.</strong> Let people undo instead of asking &ldquo;are you sure?&rdquo;</li>
</ul>

<h3>Case study: Ledger</h3>
<p>When I redesigned Ledger&rsquo;s revenue dashboard, the original had 47 visible metrics on the home screen. We reduced it to 4 &mdash; with the rest available one click away. Usage went up 3x.</p>

<p>The lesson: removing things is harder than adding them, and it&rsquo;s almost always the right call.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
    <excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[Most software is loud. Here's how to design interfaces that respect the user's time and attention.]]></excerpt:encoded>
