  <!-- ── Post 3 ──────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <item>
    <title>A Practical Guide to Design Tokens</title>
    <dc:creator>milo</dc:creator>
    <content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>Design tokens are the atoms of a design system &mdash; the smallest decisions (colours, spacing, type sizes) stored as platform-agnostic data. Here&rsquo;s how I set them up on every project.</p>

<h3>What are design tokens?</h3>
<p>A design token is a named value: <code>--color-ink: #0A0A0A</code>. It&rsquo;s not the colour itself &mdash; it&rsquo;s the <em>decision</em> to use that colour in a specific context.</p>

<h3>My token structure</h3>
<pre><code>:root {
  /* Palette */
  --green-dark:   #0E2B1A;
  --green-accent: #C6F25D;
  --paper:        #F5F2EA;
  --ink:          #0A0A0A;
  --muted:        #6A6860;

  /* Spacing */
  --space-xs: 4px;
  --space-sm: 8px;
  --space-md: 16px;
  --space-lg: 32px;
  --space-xl: 64px;

  /* Typography */
  --sans: 'Geist', sans-serif;
  --mono: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
}</code></pre>

<h3>Why bother?</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Consistency:</strong> Every component references the same source of truth.</li>
  <li><strong>Theming:</strong> Swap one file and the entire product changes.</li>
  <li><strong>Onboarding:</strong> New engineers can read the tokens and understand the visual language in minutes.</li>
</ul>

<p>Tokens aren&rsquo;t glamorous, but they&rsquo;re the foundation everything else sits on. Get them right early.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
    <excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[Design tokens are the smallest decisions in a design system. Here's how I structure them for every project.]]></excerpt:encoded>
