  <!-- ── Post 4 ──────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <item>
    <title>Accessibility Is a Design Skill</title>
    <dc:creator>milo</dc:creator>
    <content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>Accessibility isn&rsquo;t a checklist you run at the end of a project. It&rsquo;s a design skill &mdash; a lens you apply from the very first sketch.</p>

<h3>Common misconceptions</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>&ldquo;Accessible design looks boring.&rdquo;</strong> It doesn&rsquo;t. Constraints breed creativity.</li>
  <li><strong>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s only for screen readers.&rdquo;</strong> Accessibility benefits everyone: keyboard users, people in bright sunlight, users with slow connections.</li>
  <li><strong>&ldquo;We&rsquo;ll add it later.&rdquo;</strong> Retrofitting accessibility is 10x harder than building it in from the start.</li>
</ul>

<h3>My accessibility baseline</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Semantic HTML first. <code>&lt;button&gt;</code>, not <code>&lt;div onclick&gt;</code>.</li>
  <li>Colour contrast meets WCAG AA (4.5:1 for body text).</li>
  <li>All interactive elements are keyboard-navigable.</li>
  <li>Images have meaningful alt text (or <code>aria-hidden</code> if decorative).</li>
  <li><code>prefers-reduced-motion</code> is respected for all animations.</li>
</ol>

<h3>The Fieldnote project</h3>
<p>My most rewarding work was Fieldnote &mdash; a voice-first memory aid for people with aphasia, built with Mercy Hospital. It taught me that the users who need the most consideration are often the ones who get the least.</p>

<p>Every interface you build is used by someone having a harder day than you. Design for them.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
    <excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[Accessibility isn't a checklist. It's a design skill that benefits everyone.]]></excerpt:encoded>
